{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17414837","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17414837"},"attributes":{"position":43,"marks":1,"score":1,"answeredAt":"2025-09-28T09:00:12+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-28T09:00:12+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":{"type":"questionSessions","id":"1261100"}},"session":{"data":{"type":"questionSessions","id":"1261100"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"20975"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}},{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17479917","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17479917"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":1,"answeredAt":"2025-09-28T23:34:10+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-28T23:34:10+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"20975"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questionSessions","id":"1261100","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionSessions/1261100"},"attributes":{"startedAt":"2025-09-28T07:52:04+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-09-28T10:28:52+09:30","sessionType":"qbank","questionStatus":"all","difficulty":[],"timeLimit":null,"questionCount":62,"questionsAnswered":61,"marksTotal":61,"marksAttainable":61,"marksAttempted":61,"finishedAt":"2025-09-28T09:15:31+09:30","resultsAvailable":true,"score":0.2,"questionsCorrect":12,"marksCorrect":12},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"pack":{"data":{"type":"packs","id":"5"}},"exam":{"data":null}}},{"type":"questions","id":"20975","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/20975"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.23,0.39,0.03,0.17,0.18]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"13850"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"101047"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"13850","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/13850"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"20975"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"83481"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"5"},{"type":"tags","id":"9"},{"type":"tags","id":"25"},{"type":"tags","id":"66"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"1052"},{"type":"tags","id":"3696"},{"type":"tags","id":"4954"},{"type":"tags","id":"4964"},{"type":"tags","id":"4966"},{"type":"tags","id":"9636"},{"type":"tags","id":"11625"},{"type":"tags","id":"11638"},{"type":"tags","id":"13336"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"33457"},{"type":"contributions","id":"34740"},{"type":"contributions","id":"43953"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"101047","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/101047"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA two-year-old boy presents to the General Practice clinic with his parent with a one-day history of vomiting and diarrhoea. He has had four episodes of vomiting and three loose stools in the past 24 hours. He has been drinking small amounts of water but has refused food. He has no significant medical history and takes no regular medications. His immunisations are up to date.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, he appears mildly unwell. His pulse rate is 110/min, respiratory rate 24/min, and temperature 37.2\u00b0C. His mucous membranes are slightly dry, but capillary refill is less than two seconds. He has normal skin turgor and is alert and interactive. His abdomen is soft and non-tender. His weight today is 12 kg, which is the same as his documented weight from two weeks ago.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOral rehydration solution is offered but refused by the boy.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most appropriate management?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Nasogastric fluids","Dilute apple juice","Flat lemonade","Sports electrolyte drink","Intravenous normal saline"],"correctOptions":[1],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis case describes a two-year-old boy with mild dehydration (no significant clinical signs - normal weight, normal skin turgor, capillary refill \u003C2 seconds) due to gastroenteritis. The child has no contraindications to oral rehydration therapy such as severe dehydration, bilious vomiting, bloody diarrhoea, or signs of an acute abdomen.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EDilute apple juice\u003C/strong\u003E is the most appropriate option for this child. Evidence suggests that dilute apple juice (mixed 50:50 with water) is an effective alternative to oral rehydration solutions for children with mild dehydration due to gastroenteritis. A 2016 Canadian trial demonstrated that children given dilute apple juice had lower rates of treatment failure compared to those given oral rehydration solutions. This is particularly true for children over 2 years of age, like this patient, who tend to experience the greatest benefit due to taste preferences. The dilute apple juice should be administered in small 5 mL aliquots every 2-5 minutes and continued until urine output is restored. However, it is not appropriate for prolonged use as does not contain any electrolytes\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ENasogastric fluids\u003C/strong\u003E would be overly invasive for a child with mild dehydration who is still able to take oral fluids. Nasogastric rehydration is typically reserved for children who cannot tolerate oral fluids but do not require intravenous access, such as those with persistent vomiting or moderate dehydration where oral rehydration has failed.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EFlat lemonade\u003C/strong\u003E is not recommended as it has high sugar content which theoretically could worsen diarrhoea through osmotic effects. The high sugar content and lack of appropriate electrolytes make it unsuitable for rehydration in children with gastroenteritis.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOral rehydration solution has traditionally been the standard recommendation for rehydration in gastroenteritis. While effective, it often has poor palatability, which can lead to reduced intake and potentially increased need for intravenous hydration. For mild dehydration in this age group, dilute apple juice is now considered an appropriate alternative with potentially better outcomes due to increased acceptance.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EIntravenous normal saline\u003C/strong\u003E would be inappropriate for this child with mild dehydration who is still able to take oral fluids. Intravenous rehydration is reserved for children with moderate to severe dehydration, those who cannot tolerate oral fluids, or those who have failed oral rehydration therapy.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ESports electrolyte drink\u003C/strong\u003E is not recommended for rehydration in young children with gastroenteritis. Sports drinks typically contain high concentrations of carbohydrates and may have inappropriate electrolyte compositions for treating dehydration in children.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["Dilute apple juice is an effective alternative to oral rehydration solutions for mild dehydration in children aged 6 months to 5 years with gastroenteritis.","Children older than 2 years tend to experience the greatest benefit from dilute apple juice or preferred fluids due to taste preferences and lower risk of severe dehydration in the setting of mild dehydration due to gastroenteritis.","Oral rehydration solutions remain the gold standard for moderate dehydration but may be less palatable for children."],"references":["RACGP Handbook of Non-Drug Interventions: Dilute apple juice for children rehydration. First published: February 2017. Available at: https://www.racgp.org.au/clinical-resources/clinical-guidelines/handi/a-z/d/dilute-apple-juice-for-children-rehydration","Dehydration. The Royal Children\u0027s Hospital Melbourne. Last updated September 2020. Accessed at: https://www.rch.org.au/clinicalguide/guideline_index/Dehydration/","Gastroenteritis. The Royal Children\u0027s Hospital Melbourne. Last updated December 2020. Accessed at: https://www.rch.org.au/clinicalguide/guideline_index/gastroenteritis/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"83481"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"20975"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"83481","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/83481"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-04-29T22:41:25+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-05-21T13:46:37+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"13850"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"101047"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"5","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/5"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udd2d","name":"Gastroenterology","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:49:43+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"9","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/9"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udc76","name":"Paediatrics","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-01-16T08:39:03+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"25","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/25"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udc68\u200d\ud83d\udc69\u200d\ud83d\udc66","name":"General Practice","synonyms":null,"description":null,"positi